name: Nayelli Rivera
title: Endurecimiento tÃ©rmico en Pristimantis medemi (Anura: Craugastoridae), en coberturas boscosas del Municipio de Villavicencio (Meta)
notes_ID: Low altitude population. The same individuals were assessed twice for CTmax (separated by 24-48h intervals), hence why the shared cohort IDs.
notes_sampling: The sampling started from July 5th-18th  of 2018 and from June 1st – 21st of 2019.
notes_acclimation: Because the acclimation temperature was not reported and some individuals were likely tested shortly after capture, these animals were considered "field-fresh".
notes_test: Endpoint was when animals lost the ability to jump and move
flag: Animals were considered "field-fresh" but some individuals may have experienced some period of acclimation.
notes_trait: The error type was not clearly reported but it was assumed to be SD based on visual inspections of the data.

notes_sampling: Karasuk
notes_test: n_replicates_per_temp was different for each temperature. Frogs were placed in containers of 3-5 individuals, and some temperatures only have 5 or fewer individuals (Pop 1 ranges from 2-12 individuals, pop2 from 4-20 individuals, pop3 from 3-13 individuals). notes_trait: Sample size unclear. LT50 was estimated based on survival rates at different temperatures.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Allele-specific expression and gene regulation help explain transgressive thermal tolerance in non-native hybrids of the endangered California tiger salamander (Ambystoma californiense)
notes_sampling: NA
notes_acclimation:
The temperature of acclimation was not reported in the study but authors were contacted and they indicated that "Our animals were kept in a room that simulated the monthly temperatures of Jepson Prairie (California, USA). 
The mean monthly temperature regime was:
Jan: 9 °C
Feb: 10 °C
March: 12.5 °C
April: 17.5 °C
May: 20.5 °C 
June: 25.5 °C
July: 27.5 °C 
August: 27 °C 
September: 24 °C 
October: 19.5 °C 
November: 14.5 °C 
December: 10.5 °C 

Specifically we conducted the CTMax experiment in January / February, so they were acclimated to about 9-10 degrees C in the weeks before they were assayed."
notes_test: The ramping rate was not presented in the study
notes_trait: Data was taken from the results section. Note that data from hybrids was not collected.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Heat tolerance and thyroid activity in developing tadpoles and juvenile adults of xenopus laevis daudin
notes_sampling: NA
notes_acclimation: Animals were acclimated from the embryonic stage to the larval stage.
notes_test: gosner_tested was estimated based on the description of the stages (Nieuwkoop and Faber 1956) described in the paper. The n_animals_per_replicate was 30 at 36 degrees, and 50 animals at the other temperatures.
notes_trait: LT50 was calculated using survival data digitised from figure 1. I fitted a logistic regression and used the dose.p() function from 'MASS' to calculate LT50. n_trait was taken as the n_test_temp

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Critical Thermal Maximum as a Function of Temperature of Acclimation in Two Species of Hylid Frogs
notes_sampling: Sampling dates were between August 11 and August 23. Coordinates were taken from Rohr et al. 2018
notes_acclimation: Animals were acclimated for periods of 3 to 7 days, with most animals having 5-day acclimation periods.
notes_test: The endpoint was "the temperature at which no further movements of throat, abdomen, or limbs could be elicited by tapping the container against the wall of the beaker for 10 sec"
notes_trait: Data was taken from Tab 4 because Rohr et al. 2018 did not report SD. Variance was converted to standard deviation.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Evidence for a Daily Rhythm of Heat Resistance in the Cricket Frog, Acris crepitans
notes_ID: Data for animals tested at 0130hr and acclimated to 4C
notes_sampling: Geographical coordinates were estimated using Google maps, by measuring a point 12 miles North and 9 miles W of Vermillion, Clay County, South Dakota. Elevation was estimated using https://latlongdata.com/elevation/
notes_acclimation: Acclimation_time was taken as the mean of the range presented (3-5 days)
notes_test: SVL was reported as in Rohr et al. 2018 for this species. The endpoint was "the temperature at which no further movements of throat, abdomen, or limbs could be elicited by tapping the container against the wall of the beaker for 10 sec"
notes_trait: Data was digitised from figure 1. 95% confidence intervals were converted to se by dividing them by 1.96

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Thermal acclimation and tolerance in the hellbender, Cryptobranchus alleganiensis
notes_sampling: Coordinates were taken from Rohr et al. 2018. Animals were collected on 24 and 25 September 1972.
notes_acclimation: Animals were acclimated for periods of 2 to 6 weeks. The acclimation time was taken as 14 days.
notes_test: SVL was reported as in Rohr et al. 2018. Body mass was taken as the mean of the ange presented (29-644 g). Ramping was taken as 1C/min because authors state that they followed the methods of Hutchison 1961.
notes_trait: Data was taken from the main text (results section).

title: The effects of five organophosphorus insecticides on thermal stress in tadpoles of the Pacific tree frog, Hyla regilla

notes_supplements: Parts per billion (ppb) were converted to mg/L

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Variação latitudinal nos limites de tolerância e plasticidade térmica em anfíbios em um cenário de mudanças climáticas: efeito dos micro-habitats, sazonalidade e filogenia
chapter_title: Latitudinal variation of thermal tolerance limits and vulnerability to extreme temperatures in amphibians: the effects of microhabitats, seasonality and phylogeny
notes_ID: Note that data for some species was already presented in Gutiérrez-Pesquera et al 2016
notes_sampling: Geographical coordinates were not reported because too approximate (i.e. "Bahia state, 13-15°S")
notes_acclimation: acclimation_time was taken as the mean of the range presented (3-4 days)
notes_test: Gosner stage was taken as the mean of the range presented (25-38)
notes_trait: n_trait was taken as 15 because authors state that they "analyzed a minimum of 15 individuals for all 60 species for each thermal tolerance limit". However, note that this may be an overestimate in some casesbecause they also state that "for some species we study a reduced sample because shortage of field collected tadpoles".

chapter_title: Acclimation of critical thermal limits in amphibian tadpoles: it is enough to face global warming?
notes_ID: population_ID was taken as the same as in Madalozzo 2018 (chapter 1) because animals were possibly collected in the same location, and by the same researchers
notes_sampling: NA
notes_test: Gosner stage was assumed to be the same as in chapter I of the thesis (25-38)
notes_trait: Data was digitised from figure 1A. n_trait was taken as reported in Table 2 for the lowest and highest acclimation temperatures. For the intermediate acclimation temperatures (i.e. 15C, 20C, 20/27C for the temperate, subtropical and tropical populations, respectively), the lowest sample size presented in Table 2 was reported as a conservative measure. 95% confidence intervals were converted to sd in with metadigitise.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Environmental and genetic influences on the thermal physiology of Rana sylvatica
notes_ID: New York (Rensselaerville) population. The same individuals were used for measuring LRR, OS and HR, hence the shared cohort IDs.
notes_sampling: Coordinates were converted to decimal degrees using the data in Table 1
notes_test: Gosner_tested was taken as the mean of the range presented (33-36)
notes_trait: Data was digitised from figure 2 because SD was not reported in Rohr et al. 2018. 95% confidence intervals were converted to se by dividing them by 2 (see figure legend of figure 3 suggesting that 95% CI were calculated as 2SE). Data from figure 3 was not included because it was unclear what temperature the animals were acclimated to.

name: PPollo
title: Standardized ethograms and a device for assessing amphibian thermal responses in a warming world
notes_sampling: Animals were sampled from 19°15'02"N to 19°34'04"N (latitude) and 96°59'44"W to 96°49'13"W (longitude). The midpoint of these coordinates was taken here.
notes_env_temp: Ambient and microhabitat (substrate) temperature were presented in Table S4.
notes_test: The endpoint was the complete immobility and rigidity of the body of the animals. SVL was taken as the mean of the range presented in the main text.
notes_trait: Individual data points were digitised from figure 6 by PP.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Natural daily temperature acclimation of eastern red efts, Notophthalmus V. viridescens (rafinesque) (Amphibia: Caudata)
notes_ID: Data for animals collected in the morning of Cloudy day 1. The same individuals were tested for LRR (5 seconds), LRR (15 seconds) and heat rigor, hence the shared cohort IDs.
notes_sampling: Coordinates were taken from Rohr et al. 2018.
notes_test: SVL was reported as in Rohr et al. 2018. Endpoint was when it took animals longer than 5 seconds to right themselves.
notes_trait: Data was digitised from figure 2 because SD was not reported in Rohr et al. 2018. Data for dehydrated/rehydrated animals and animals maintained at 19C were not included because the methods were not described.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: High temperature tolerances of Bufo hemiophrys and Bufo cognatus
notes_sampling: Geographical coordinates were approximated using Google Maps.
notes_test: The n_animals_per_replicate varied at the different test temperatures (4, 5, 9, 10, and 4 individuals tested at 43.5, 42, 40, 38 and 36C respectively). Here is noted the lowest sample size as a conservative measure.
flag: Estimates converted using the thermal tolerance landscape framework
notes_trait: Data was digitised from figure 2. Note that the data was digitised using WebPlotDigitizer because the extraction with metaDigitise was inaccurate. Survival time data was converted to CTmax using the thermal tolerance landscape framework. Data calculated by fitting a linear regression of log10(time to death) against the test temperatures according to Jorgensen et al. 2018,2021 and Rezende et al. 2014. The CTmax was estimated as the temperatures animals cannot withstand for longer than 60 minutes. The sample size was taken as the n_test_temp * n_replicates_per_temp.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Upper thermal tolerance plasticity in tropical amphibian species from contrasting habitats: implications for warming impact prediction
notes_sampling: Elevation estimated from https://latlongdata.com/elevation/

name: Pietro Pollo
title: BALANCING HYPOXIA AND HYPOTHERMIA IN COLD-SUBMERGED FROGS
notes_ID: The same animals were tested at different time points, hence the shared cohort IDs
notes_sampling: Animals were "obtained from commercial suppliers (Blades Biological Co., UK), who collected the animals from natural populations in Ireland in the autumn of 1995". Coordinates were estimated from Google Maps.
notes_test: Normoxia (158 mmHg). Experiment lasted for 40h but figure with results only shows observations for 6h; sample size was 6 individuals but figure 1 shows number of total observations (in 6h), knowing there were 15 observations per hour, there were 540 (6*6*15) observations shown in figure 1; two treatments: normoxia (158mmHg) and hypoxia (25mmHg) but with the same individuals (started in normoxia [figure 1B] then were subjected to hypoxia [figure 1C]); individuals from figure 1A were actually in a constant temperature setting.
notes_trait: Data was digitised from the figure, which only presented the % of observations. Therefore, standard error was based on a sample size of 100, but n_trait was taken as NA.

Experiment lasted for 40h but figure with results only shows observations for 6h; sample size was 6 individuals but figure 1 shows number of total observations (in 6h), knowing there were 15 observations per hour, there were 540 (6*6*15) observations shown in figure 1; two treatments: normoxia (158mmHg) and hypoxia (25mmHg) but with the same individuals (started in normoxia [figure 1B] then were subjected to hypoxia [figure 1C]); individuals from figure 1A were actually in a constant temperature setting.

name: Pietro Pollo
title: BEHAVIORAL THERMOREGULATION BY BUFO AMERICANUS: THE IMPORTANCE OF THE HYDRIC ENVIRONMENT
notes_ID: The same animals were tested at different time points, hence the shared cohort IDs
notes_sampling: Animals were collected from permanent pond (Van Pond) near the University of Michigan Biological Station (UMBS) at Douglas Lake, Pellston, Michigan. Coordinates were estimated from Google Maps
notes_test: wet sand (soil water potential = 0kPa);  different groups depending on substrate: "(1) the sandy substratum of the gradient was saturated with water (soil water potential = 0 kPa); (2) sand in a portion of the gradient was dry (soil water potential < -1000 kPa), and a portion was saturated; and (3) all of the sand in the gradient was dry"; second treatment not extracted because there is preference for substrate and temperature at the same time (see figure 4); number of total observations should have been between 450 to 540 (5 groups * 6 individuals * 18-19 observations each), but that's not what I got from the histograms in figure 3 (I maintained the sample size from the figure extraction); figure 3b-f are from the same experiment but different "blocks" of observations (each with 10 min); body temperature was estimated from regressions that assessed the relationsip between substrate temperature and body temperature
notes_trait: NA

notes_test: dry sand 5th 10 min block. soil water potential < -1000 kPa; different groups depending on substrate: "(1) the sandy substratum of the gradient was saturated with water (soil water potential = 0 kPa); (2) sand in a portion of the gradient was dry (soil water potential < -1000 kPa), and a portion was saturated; and (3) all of the sand in the gradient was dry"; second treatment not extracted because there is preference for substrate and temperature at the same time (see figure 4);  number of total observations should have been between 450 to 540 (5 groups * 6 individuals * 18-19 observations each), but that's not what I got from the histograms in figure 3 (I maintained the sample size from the figure extraction); figure 3b-f are from the same experiment but different "blocks" of observations (each with 10 min); body temperature was estimated from regressions that assessed the relationsip between substrate temperature and body temperature
notes_trait: NA

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Divergence of thermal physiological traits in terrestrial breeding frogs along a tropical elevational gradient
notes_sampling: Geographical coordinates were not clearly reported. Only the location of some key Peruvian study sites were presented, but it was impossible to assign each site to a particular species. However, geographical coordinates are provided for the same species (and most likely for the same population in Rohr et al. 2018 (data from Catenazzi et al. 2014). The midpoint elevation was taken from Tab S3.
notes_acclimation: acclimation_time was taken as the mean of the range presented (2-3 days). Acclimation temperature was 16-21C so we taken the mean acclimation temperature and used SD_acclimation_temp was the variation around that mean
notes_test: NA
notes_trait: n_trait was approximated as the total number of individuals tested (768) divided by the number of species tested (22) and rounded down.
